# Leash — Robot Harness

## Product

A Rust harness runtime for robot control. Leash is built Rust-first, MCP-first, and simulation-safe. It exposes robot hardware through a CLI/HTTP server, MCP stdio interface, and localhost MCP HTTP control surface. LLM agents command physical robots through pilot-token-authorized sessions. Feature-gated hardware adapters (Waveshare UGV first, then quadrupeds, humanoids, drones, arms). Safety gates at every layer (deadman, estop, soft-odometry-limit, physical-actuation-gate). Sim-safe by default — zero hardware required.

Leash targets a generic robotics operating surface: typed modules, reusable stacks, replay, local-agent control, telemetry, and explicit physical safety boundaries.

## What the User Sees

### Interface: CLI

```
$ leash serve mcp
[leash] profile: sim, role: robot
[leash] safety gates: deadman(400ms), estop, soft-odometry-limit(0.0m), physical-gate(off)
[leash] MCP stdio ready

$ leash serve http --listen 127.0.0.1:8000
[leash] profile: sim, role: robot
[leash] HTTP server listening on 127.0.0.1:8000
[leash] endpoints: /health, /capabilities, /telemetry, /drive, /estop, /ws/telemetry, ...

$ leash serve mcp-http --listen 127.0.0.1:9990
[leash] MCP HTTP server listening on 127.0.0.1:9990

$ leash mcp status --url http://127.0.0.1:9990
{ "ok": true, "transport": "mcp-http", "tool_count": 8, ... }

$ leash mcp call invoke_capability capability=authorize token=demo ttl_secs=30
{ "ok": true, "tool": "invoke_capability", "result": { "ok": true, "ttl_secs": 30, ... } }

$ leash mcp call invoke_capability --policy-mode dry-run capability=drive left=0.2 right=0.2
{ "ok": true, "tool": "invoke_capability", "result": { "ok": true, "dry_run": true, ... } }

$ leash health --url http://127.0.0.1:8000
{ "ok": true, "role": "robot", "profile": "sim", "uptime_ms": 12043, "estop": false, ... }

$ leash agent-send "inspect the battery"
{ "ok": true, "message": { "id": 1, "source": "cli", "text": "inspect the battery", ... }, "response": { "provider": "deterministic-test", ... } }

$ LEASH_AGENT_API_KEY=... leash show-config --agent-provider openai-compatible-http --agent-base-url https://example.test/v1
{ "agent_provider": "openai-compatible-http", "fields": [{ "name": "agent_api_key", "value": "<redacted>", ... }] }

$ leash show-config --policy-mode require-approval
{ "policy_mode": "require-approval", "fields": [{ "name": "policy_mode", "source": "cli", ... }] }

$ leash stop --url http://127.0.0.1:8000
{ "ok": true, "left": 0.0, "right": 0.0, ... }
```

### Interface: MCP (LLM Agent)

```
Tool: health           → harness health and safety state
Tool: capabilities     → endpoints, MCP tools, speed modes
Tool: modules          → module graph and stream metadata
Tool: observe          → latest telemetry frame (odometry, battery, sensors)
Tool: invoke_capability → authorize, drive, stop, estop, estop_reset, speed_mode
Tool: stop             → non-latching zero-speed motor stop
Tool: estop            → latch emergency stop
Tool: capture          → deterministic frame capture (SVG)
```

### Interface: HTTP REST

```
GET  /health              → Health struct
GET  /capabilities         → Capabilities struct
GET  /telemetry            → TelemetryFrame (latest)
GET  /events/telemetry     → SSE TelemetryStreamFrame
GET  /sse/telemetry        → alias for /events/telemetry
GET  /sensors              → sensor snapshot
GET  /camera/status        → camera health + stream URLs
GET  /                    → server-rendered command center dashboard
GET  /dashboard            → server-rendered command center dashboard
GET  /agent                → localhost web input form
GET  /agent/messages       → recent AgentMessage list
POST /agent/messages       → { source, text } → AgentMessageAck
POST /dashboard/authorize  → form post → authorize capability
POST /dashboard/stop       → form post → stop capability
POST /dashboard/estop      → form post → estop capability
POST /dashboard/estop-reset → form post → estop_reset capability
POST /dashboard/capture    → form post → capture capability
POST /capture              → CaptureResult (SVG frame + sha256)
POST /pilot/authorize      → { token, ttl_secs, speed_mode } → PilotTokenResp
POST /pilot/speed-mode     → { token, speed_mode }
POST /drive                → { token, left, right, speed_mode, approval } → DriveOutcome
POST /motors/drive         → alias for /drive
POST /motors/stop          → DriveOutcome (zeroed)
POST /stop                 → alias for /motors/stop
POST /estop                → { ok: true, estop: true }
POST /estop/reset          → { token, approval } → { ok: true, estop: false }
GET  /stream               → SVG frame (image/svg+xml)
WS   /ws/telemetry         → streaming TelemetryStreamFrame JSON with visualization payload
```

## User Stories

| ID | Story | Pri | Acceptance |
|----|-------|-----|------------|
| LS-01 | Operator starts harness with `leash serve mcp` | P0 | MCP stdio ready, tools respond |
| LS-01a | Operator starts localhost MCP HTTP with `leash serve mcp-http` | P0 | `/mcp/tools` lists tools, `/mcp/call` invokes health/stop |
| LS-02 | LLM agent commands rover motor via MCP invoke_capability | P0 | Speed-capped, deadman-enforced drive |
| LS-03 | Operator hits estop via CLI/MCP | P0 | All motors halt, estop latched until reset |
| LS-04 | Operator runs sim profile with zero hardware | P0 | Telemetry streams, drive commands log only |
| LS-05 | Hardware vendor enables Waveshare UGV | P1 | `--features waveshare-ugv` + `--allow-physical-actuation` |
| LS-06 | CI smoke-tests MCP, HTTP, MCP HTTP, agent input, CLI calls, and physical gate | P1 | `smoke-http.sh`, `smoke-mcp.sh`, `smoke-mcp-http.sh`, `smoke-physical-gate.sh` |
| LS-07 | Package published to crates.io | P2 | `cargo install leash-harness` works |
| LS-08 | Binary release on GitHub | P2 | Download + run, no Rust toolchain needed |
| LS-09 | Developer defines a module with typed inputs/outputs | P1 | Module appears in module graph with correct streams |
| LS-10 | Operator runs a stack in sim mode | P1 | Full nav pipeline executes without hardware |
| LS-11 | Developer replays a recorded session | P2 | Replay reproduces exact telemetry stream |
| LS-12 | Operator views live telemetry via WebSocket | P0 | `ws://127.0.0.1:8000/ws/telemetry` streams frames |
| LS-13 | Integrator bridges external transport | P2 | Cross-process module communicates over TCP |
| LS-14 | Human sends natural-language input into a local runtime | P1 | `agent-send`, `agent-interactive`, and `/agent` route messages without an LLM provider |
| LS-15 | Developer configures a model provider without leaking secrets | P1 | deterministic provider works in CI; hosted/local config validates; API key is redacted |
| LS-16 | Operator policy-gates physical capability invocation | P0 | safety classes include physical-high-risk; modes support dry-run, require-token, require-approval, deny; stop/estop remain available |
| LS-17 | Operator opens a localhost command center | P1 | `/dashboard` renders health, telemetry, modules, capabilities, logs, and stop/estop controls without client JavaScript |
| LS-18 | External viewer subscribes to telemetry stream frames | P1 | frames include `leash-visualization-v1` pose, path, occupancy-grid, point-cloud metadata, detections, and command overlay payloads |
